<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    This module ships ONE deliberate legacy counter-example whose contract violations ARE the lesson,
    so the characterization and behaviour-preservation tests can prove the refactoring the prose
    describes rather than merely assert it. The detectors are left fully ENABLED for the rest of the
    module (the modern ShippingCalculator, the value types, the sealed Quote hierarchy, the strangler
    router all stay clean); only the named legacy class carries findings, suppressed narrowly, with a
    reason, and pointed at the tests that demonstrate why they matter. Refactoring the class — which
    ShippingCalculator already does — is the real advice; the suppression exists only so the teaching
    counter-example can ship green.
  -->

  <!--
    LegacyShippingCalculator hands its internal mutable surcharge list back from appliedSurcharges(),
    so a caller can mutate the calculator's state through the returned reference — the kind of
    representation-exposure leak the modern refactor closes with an immutable snapshot. At this module's
    threshold SpotBugs raises EI_EXPOSE_REP on the accessor; EI_EXPOSE_REP2 (the store-side pattern) is
    matched too in case a stricter threshold raises it. Proven by
    SafeChangeTest#legacyCalculatorLeaksItsInternalSurchargeList. The fix is the unmodifiable snapshot in
    ShippingCalculator (List.of / List.copyOf), never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.refactoring.LegacyShippingCalculator"/>
    <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP,EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
